        "client_msg_id": "c2755577-a806-4f13-884d-7804a92d5ae2",
        "type": "message",
        "text": "I don't think \"can't experiment with unusual interfaces\" is what we should be concerned about, it's more \"competition to make a better thing\".\n\nBut personally I'm in the camp of \"give 90% of the users something simple, consistent and effective for 90% of their needs, but allow extension for edge cases and those difficult ones (like me!)\" If you don't have apps at all, then you're kinda forced into cross-datatype interaction consistency. Which is good IMHO.\n\nAnd yes, \"itemized\" is (part of) the future! There's another thread talking about Obenauer's stuff just now.\n\nAnd exactly as you say, it's also the past - the TBL Web didn't have \"apps\" like today's web pages have. Today, each page is not really part of a seamless web any more.",
        "user": "UE6EFEPTQ",
        "ts": "1700644583.127659",
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "PB3AM",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "I don't think \"can't experiment with unusual interfaces\" is what we should be concerned about, it's more \"competition to make a better thing\".\n\nBut personally I'm in the camp of \"give 90% of the users something simple, consistent and effective for 90% of their needs, but allow extension for edge cases and those difficult ones (like me!)\" If you don't have apps at all, then you're kinda forced into cross-datatype interaction consistency. Which is good IMHO.\n\nAnd yes, \"itemized\" is (part of) the future! There's another thread talking about Obenauer's stuff just now.\n\nAnd exactly as you say, it's also the past - the TBL Web didn't have \"apps\" like today's web pages have. Today, each page is not really part of a seamless web any more."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
